{
  "Metadata": {
    "QuestionTitle": "Sum of Infinite Geometric Progression and Arithmetic Progression",
    "Source": "Cambridge International AS & A Level Mathematics: Pure Mathematics 1 Past Paper",
    "ExamBoard": "CAIE",
    "SyllabusCode": "9709",
    "Subject": "MATH",
    "YearOfExam": 2022,
    "Session": "October/November",
    "PaperNumber": "Paper 1",
    "QuestionNumber": 9,
    "QuestionType": "Structured Question",
    "Level": "P1",
    "MathTopic": "Progressions",
    "TopicsCovered": [
      "Geometric Progression",
      "Arithmetic Progression"
    ],
    "MarksAllocation": {
      "PartA": 3,
      "PartB": 6
    },
    "DifficultyLevel": "Moderate",
    "ImageUrl": [
      "/9709_P1_2022_Nov_13/q9.png"
    ]
  },
  "QuestionContent": {
    "Parts": [
      {
        "Part": "a",
        "Text": "The first term of a geometric progression is 216 and the fourth term is 64. Find the sum to infinity of the progression."
      },
      {
        "Part": "b",
        "Text": "The second term of the geometric progression is equal to the second term of an arithmetic progression. The third term of the geometric progression is equal to the fifth term of the same arithmetic progression.\n\nFind the sum of the first 21 terms of the arithmetic progression."
      }
    ]
  },
  "SolutionContent": {
    "Parts": [
      {
        "Part": "a",
        "Solution": [
          "\\( 216r^3 = 64 \\Rightarrow r = \\frac{2}{3} \\)",
          "The sum to infinity of the geometric progression is given by \\( S_\\infty = \\frac{a}{1-r} \\):",
          "\\[ S_\\infty = \\frac{216}{1 - \\frac{2}{3}} = \\frac{216}{\\frac{1}{3}} = 648. \\]"
        ],
        "MarkingScheme": {
          "B1": "Correct value of \\(r\\).",
          "M1": "Correct formula and substitution for \\(S_\\infty\\).",
          "A1": "Final correct value of \\(S_\\infty\\)."
        }
      },
      {
        "Part": "b",
        "Solution": [
          "For the arithmetic progression, the second term is \\( 216 \\cdot \\frac{2}{3} = 144 \\), so \\( a + d = 144 \\).",
          "The third term of the GP is \\( 216 \\cdot \\left(\\frac{2}{3}\\right)^2 = 96 \\), equal to the fifth term of the AP:",
          "\\[ a + 4d = 96. \\]",
          "Solving \\( a + d = 144 \\) and \\( a + 4d = 96 \\):",
          "\\[ d = -16, \\quad a = 160. \\]",
          "The sum of the first 21 terms is given by:",
          "\\[ S_{21} = \\frac{n}{2} (2a + (n-1)d): \\]",
          "\\[ S_{21} = \\frac{21}{2} \\cdot (2 \\cdot 160 + (21 - 1) \\cdot -16): \\]",
